docs.abstract: They hold signs at protest marches, but they are also volunteering to strategize for a State Assembly race, and even running for office.
docs.snippet: They hold signs at protest marches, but they are also volunteering to strategize for a State Assembly race, and even running for office.
docs.lead_paragraph: When photos began circulating of migrant children separated from their parents and placed in what looked like giant cages in detention centers, the young adult novelists Melissa de la Cruz and Margaret Stohl had an immediate response. After texting nine author friends asking what they could collectively do, Ms. de la Cruz and Ms. Stohl drafted a statement of protest called “Kidlit Says No Kids in Cages,” denouncing “practices that should be restricted to the pages of dystopian novels.”

headline.main: Children’s Book Authors Are Selling More Than Books. They’re Taking a Stand.
headline.print_headline: Children’s Authors Aren’t Just Signing Books. They’re Signing Petitions, Too.

docs.lead_paragraph: Last year NBC canceled “The Carmichael Show,” an inspired throwback to the era of politically charged Norman Lear sitcoms like “All in the Family” and “Good Times,” after three seasons. The show, starring the standup comedian Jerrod Carmichael, who is also one of the creators, was never a ratings bonanza, but it was praised for its sharp, multifaceted takes on a wide range of hot-button issues, including sexual consent, abortion and euthanasia.

headline.main: Lil Rel Howery and Jerrod Carmichael Think You’re Wrong About Multicamera Sitcoms
